norders for all our products. As belligerent\ngovernments bid against each\nother the movement was accelerated.\nWin n we entered the conflict in such a\nColossal way business tied the heaviest\nweight to be had to the safety valve\nand everything went ahead w,f,i full\nsteam until the day of the ..istic-e.\nFollowing that eventful day business\npaused for a brief spell, ani'i it seemed 1\nfor a few weeks as If we might get our\nbearings and start on the way to a peace 1\nbasis. Vain hope 1 How much better it\nwould have been if wo hgtf Tho mo-j\nmentum that l ad been gathered by the\nwar would not let the machine slon\"\"\ndown. With paper fortunes for nearly\nU illi omv-Mininiils Iin.ihle to\nreduce their expenditures, with huge out- 1\nlays of capital expenditures, with unskilled\nlabor drawing compensation\nefjual to that uf trained and experienced\nex- entires, tliej-e dawned what might be\ntermed \"The Automobile-Silk Shirt Age.\"\nHnxliiesa I.oscs Head.\n\".Many business men were swept off\ntheir feet. College professors, statisticians\nand economists produced bales of\nfigures and arguments Jo prove that a\nnow day had dawned and that prices\nnever would drop to a pre-war level.\n\"The most serious obstacle confront- I\nins us In the present situation is the\nfeet that our productive capacity is'\ngeared tip to about 30 per rent, more\n(ban our home consumption. Our na- I\ntional prosperity will be measured by\nour ability to develop stable foreign\nmarkets for our surplps production.\n\"Prior to the war our principal foreign\ncustomer- were Kngland, Oermariy.\nFrance, Kus.sii. Italy e I Austria-Hun-\ns-iry. The latest rcl .',|e figures a* to\nthe financial condition of these countries\nare not encouraging:\nNations' National\nWealth Debt p r\nfotiutry. Pillion*. Million* t's,nt.\nKttelaml 3.0 17 30 04]\nrmsny 30 03'. 312.if.\nfiance inn (I ll.'tf'\nRussia At too in.on 1\nllal -to tn.'fs) in. no 1\nAustt iu Hungary I 2li 2.tiO0.00\n461 22{.r0.o\nt'ompared with the other belligerent\nnations wo canto out of the war almost\nnnscratched. both us to our man-power\nand wealth. The financial and business\nsituation of these Buropea.it nations is i\ngloomy, but they fane the future with\ncourage. They must have help. They\nask for credit, not for alms; they ask\nfor -ration, not for charity. 'Help\nus to lp ourselves' is their only plea. I\nTheir !<t* must produce more raw matt\nrials. The fires in their furnace must\nh.- rekindled. Tin; shuttles In their loom*\niimat ho restarted hp'I uuk-kened. The\nconfidence of commerce must bring to-\ngether nations in barter and trade.\ntl itht t??lat Europe'\nW i cannot answer their appeal with 1\n'I int not my brother's keeper.* Such an\nanswer in rot in keeping with our rellgioua\nprinciples nor tie- Meals of our i\ns neroua ami just American people. I\nMoreover, our own welfare and business t\nprosperity are too elngel.v Interwoven\nwith their fate to permit anything but j\nstimulating at stragetlc service.\n\"Mow wel' o wo equipped to help in]\nthe rcatorai .1 of Europe? Otu- national\nwealth I* est hnatt ?l as high as\nJ,Oft.Mio.o i)0.000 our national debt. 1\n$2t.OCO.OOO.Oiift?a marc trifle compared!\nto t'lelis. Tti a large way our future\nprosperity depend a on theiis and will ha\nantiRctl to a certain extent by our wllllitanse*\nto help tliem.\n\"The j>:?s.-xgr of tltc l->tg>- act permittirg\ntl net.) potation of large, fcu-lgn\ntrade \"tnau corporations is citpstruc1\nu- le--.- itton. Already one such tomian>\nbis oeaa organized under Its prot\n?ioj In N't-w York with 1 capital of\noa.Oftii. M-oilier is lieiuft otgautzed\nn New uridine with a capital ot 8C.OOtl.ftO\n1. I niti 1 the au-i?!'f? of I'->\nAmerican Hankers VtutociatloQ. anotlv\none. of coins*a 1 aiie. with a nationwide.\nIICT Ititt and 11 t Ll it a I of ItftO 000.000.\nis Iteu.g or* tni^ad. Tli**e companies\nshould l?c srcut factors iu the conduct'\nof nnr forelfti trad* and commerce.\n\"Tho financial and Industria