e thp outbreak\nof the war in Kurope, is tlic opinion of i\nJames S. Alexander, president of the I\nNational Bank of Commerce In New\nYork.\nMr. Alexander outlined yesterday hi3\nviews In a nummary of 192U, which he\npresented to the hank's directors in their\nrecent organization meeting. \"The future\ndoes not hold an expectation of a\nreturn to the abnormal activity of the\nlatter part of 1919 and the early months\nof 1 920 and a return to those conditions\nwould not be deshirbje,\" he declared.\n\"A large part of the profits of that\nperiod hae been Illusory and a large\npart of the apparent business development\nhas been unhealthy and out of\nproportion.\"\nfn discussing affairs of the bank Mr.\nAlexander said that it had not turned\nIts back 011 any good and solvent customer.\neven though circumstances offered\nan excuse for so doing. \"No business\ninterest identified with this bank.\"\nhe said, \"has been refused audi, cooperation\nas its condition and prospects\"\nhave merited and general circumstances\nhave-justified.\n\"Confident reliance on the reserve\nsystem as a practical and efficient reenforcement\nof courageous banking\nlia? male it possible to pursue a policy\ndetermined on the broadest grounds of\nthe general financial wad tare.\"\nROAD SPURNS TOLEDO\nPROPOSAL TO BUY LINE\nThe Toledo Railways anil t.ipht Com-1\npany. owned by the Cities Service Com- j\nDany. has declined to accept the new\nToledo ordinance taking over the street\nf:ar lines of Toledo and has requested J\na special meeting of the City Council, in\nwhich it will voice its objections.\nTolodq voters on November 2 adopted'\nan ordinance that rested the Oommu-\nnity Traction Company, and provided\nliiai ii?! propel'iii'K uniiw u.\\ wie luicuu i\nRailways and Light Company Is* ?v?n\nov 1 operated by the city for!\nSS.noj.oyy of fi per cent, bonds and an\nia?i e of per cent, preferred stock, of i\nwhich $500,099 wis to be issued at once.\nBy the terms of that ordinance the\ncity would op